al force-application setups: it is a marked hole/point where loops (wire/thread) attach near A to apply force with a Newton balance, indicating that the same label is reused for both conceptual kinematics and hands-on mechanics measurement. [Data: Entities (1536, 1537); Relationships (2287, 2291)]\"},{\"summary\":\"A→B→C walking scenarios connect direction entities (EAST, NORTH) to displacement and distance learning objectives\",\"explanation\":\"The community includes a canonical two-leg motion example where a CHILD travels from POINT A to POINT B eastward, then from POINT B to POINT C northward. The relationships explicitly bind EAST to reaching POINT B and NORTH to reaching POINT C, making direction an integral part of interpreting displacement as a vector rather than only a path length. [Data: Entities (511, 536, 538, 506, 507,+more); Relationships (622, 623, 617, 620, 642,+more)]\\n\\nThe same A→B→C scenario is formalized as an exercise prompt (Exercise 2.1) and as a named motion event (MOTION FROM A TO C), indicating that the example is used to drive computations of total distance traversed versus straight-line displacement from start to finish. [Data: Entities (534, 557, 535); Relationships (589, 642, 591)]\"},{\"summary\":\"Distance vs displacement is illustrated through multiple route/path constructs, including alternative paths between the same endpoints\",\"explanation\":\"Figure-based entities describe alternative routes (PATH P/Q/R) between POINT A and POINT B with different distances, while maintaining a consistent displacement determined only by the endpoints. This explicitly operationalizes the distinction: distance depends on the chosen path, displacement depends only on initial and final position. [Data: Entities (512, 508, 509, 510, 525); Relationships (544, 546, 547, 548, 549,+more)]\\n\\nThe network also includes a separate example (Figure 2.3) where the traveled distance (400 m) differs from the straight-line displacement magnitude (120 m) from